<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-362-118  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 362 118.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  June 1989 v62 n6 p74(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It's time to grow up. (why software is often late to market)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shandle, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Software packages are often behind schedule in getting to marketbecause the techniques used to manage development projects areinadequate for the complexity of newer software.andP;  Software housesare still using the ad hoc or intuitive management that worked adecade or more ago for small teams working on small projects.andO;Coordinating larger numbers of programmers working on more complexprograms, and planning and evaluating those programs, requiresmore disciplined management.andP;  The Software Engineering Instituteat Carnegie-Mellon University has devised a scale with which torate the maturity and type of management at software developmentfirms.andP;  Level One on the scale indicates ad hoc management withits consequent high degree of risk, while Level Five is theoptimal management level.andP;  No software houses studied by the SEIhave reached Level Four or Level Five.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Product DevelopmentSoftware PackagesProject ManagementIndustry AnalysisSoftware Publishers.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   How the software developers are doing. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>